<div id="review_624990293" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/624990293" />
    <a title="F" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12406809-f"><img alt="F" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/624990293?book_show_action=true">May 26, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="F" class="user" itemprop="url" name="F" href="/user/show/12406809-f">F</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9783518100493" href="/book/show/241114.Mutter_Courage_und_ihre_Kinder">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer624990293" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17661475599615315257">I read this 40 years ago or more. Coming back to it, I realised how much I had missed the first time round, and how powerful a play it is. Written by Brecht in exile just before the Second World War, and given its first performance in Germany in the late 1940s, his attempt to tackle questions such as &apos;mitmachen&apos;/collaboration and &apos;war as business&apos; entertain his audience/reader as well as stimulating them to profound reflection. He does not give clear answers. I think his intention is not to prov</span>
  <span id="freeText17661475599615315257" style="display:none">I read this 40 years ago or more. Coming back to it, I realised how much I had missed the first time round, and how powerful a play it is. Written by Brecht in exile just before the Second World War, and given its first performance in Germany in the late 1940s, his attempt to tackle questions such as 'mitmachen'/collaboration and 'war as business' entertain his audience/reader as well as stimulating them to profound reflection. He does not give clear answers. I think his intention is not to provide 'realistic' lovable appealing characters. He uses drama as a means to think and to provoke thought and Mutter Courage does this in buckets for me.<br />I will be rereading this and hoping to see it performed.I have seen it staged previously, but not recently.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17661475599615315257" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


